-- 
Oil Volatility Falls Amid Futures Drop as Refinery Concern Ebbs

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-05-16T21:07:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-16/oil-volatility-falls-amid-futures-drop-as-refinery-concern-ebbs.html
Oil options volatility declined as
the underlying futures fell after the opening of spillways
reduced concern that the  Mississippi River  will flood regional
refineries.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 36 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New York , down
from 36.1 percent May 13.  Crude oil for June delivery dropped $2.28, or 2.3 percent,
to settle at $97.37 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile
Exchange , the lowest settlement since May 6. Prices have risen
36 percent in the past year.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
June $95 puts, with 3,695 lots changing hands. They slipped 1
cent to 25 cents a barrel. June $100 calls, the next-most active
option, dropped $1.18 to 10 cents a barrel with 3,061 lots
trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  July $115 calls were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 9,484 lots changing hands. They fell 9
cents to 60 cents a barrel. The next-most active option, July
$110 calls, fell 10 cents to $1.20 a barrel on 8,803 lots.  Open interest was highest for December 2012 $80 puts with
45,830 contracts. Next were June $150 calls with 44,097 and
December $120 calls with 41,257.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at   mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 